"Bálint M., Domisch S., Engelhardt C.H.M., Haase P., Lehrian S., Sauer J., Theissinger K., Pauls S.U., Nowak C.","Cryptic biodiversity loss linked to global climate change",2011,"Nature Climate Change","1","6",,"313","318",,,10.1038/nclimate1191,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-84856885753&partnerID=40&md5=9588fd3721acd7cc5058f051ea099978","Biodiversity and Climate Research Centre (BiK-F), Senckenberganlage 25, 60325 Frankfurt am Main, Germany; Molecular Biology Center, Babeş-Bolyai University, Treboniu Laurian 42, 400271 Cluj, Romania; Senckenberg Research Institutes and Natural History Museums, Department of Limnology and Conservation, Clamecystrasse 12, 63571 Gelnhausen, Germany; Institute of Zoology, Department of Ecology, Johannes Gutenberg-University Mainz, Becherweg 13, 55128 Mainz, Germany; Institute for Environmental Sciences, University of Koblenz-Landau, Fortstrasse 7, 76829 Landau, Germany","Bálint, M., Biodiversity and Climate Research Centre (BiK-F), Senckenberganlage 25, 60325 Frankfurt am Main, Germany, Molecular Biology Center, Babeş-Bolyai University, Treboniu Laurian 42, 400271 Cluj, Romania; Domisch, S., Biodiversity and Climate Research Centre (BiK-F), Senckenberganlage 25, 60325 Frankfurt am Main, Germany, Senckenberg Research Institutes and Natural History Museums, Department of Limnology and Conservation, Clamecystrasse 12, 63571 Gelnhausen, Germany; Engelhardt, C.H.M., Senckenberg Research Institutes and Natural History Museums, Department of Limnology and Conservation, Clamecystrasse 12, 63571 Gelnhausen, Germany; Haase, P., Biodiversity and Climate Research Centre (BiK-F), Senckenberganlage 25, 60325 Frankfurt am Main, Germany, Senckenberg Research Institutes and Natural History Museums, Department of Limnology and Conservation, Clamecystrasse 12, 63571 Gelnhausen, Germany; Lehrian, S., Senckenberg Research Institutes and Natural History Museums, Department of Limnology and Conservation, Clamecystrasse 12, 63571 Gelnhausen, Germany; Sauer, J., Biodiversity and Climate Research Centre (BiK-F), Senckenberganlage 25, 60325 Frankfurt am Main, Germany; Theissinger, K., Institute of Zoology, Department of Ecology, Johannes Gutenberg-University Mainz, Becherweg 13, 55128 Mainz, Germany, Institute for Environmental Sciences, University of Koblenz-Landau, Fortstrasse 7, 76829 Landau, Germany; Pauls, S.U., Biodiversity and Climate Research Centre (BiK-F), Senckenberganlage 25, 60325 Frankfurt am Main, Germany; Nowak, C., Biodiversity and Climate Research Centre (BiK-F), Senckenberganlage 25, 60325 Frankfurt am Main, Germany, Senckenberg Research Institutes and Natural History Museums, Department of Limnology and Conservation, Clamecystrasse 12, 63571 Gelnhausen, Germany","Global climate change (GCC) significantly affects distributional patterns of organisms, and considerable impacts on biodiversity are predicted for the next decades. Inferred effects include large-scale range shifts towards higher altitudes and latitudes, facilitation of biological invasions and species extinctions. Alterations of biotic patterns caused by GCC have usually been predicted on the scale of taxonomically recognized morphospecies. However, the effects of climate change at the most fundamental level of biodiversity - intraspecific genetic diversity - remain elusive. Here we show that the use of morphospecies-based assessments of GCC effects will result in underestimations of the true scale of biodiversity loss. Species distribution modelling and assessments of mitochondrial DNA variability in nine montane aquatic insect species in Europe indicate that future range contractions will be accompanied by severe losses of cryptic evolutionary lineages and genetic diversity within these lineages. These losses greatly exceed those at the scale of morphospecies. We also document that the extent of range reduction may be a useful proxy when predicting losses of genetic diversity. Our results demonstrate that intraspecific patterns of genetic diversity should be considered when estimating the effects of climate change on biodiversity. © 2011 Macmillan Publishers Limited. All rights reserved.",,"altitude; biodiversity; biological invasion; climate change; facilitation; genetic variation; global change; intraspecific variation; latitude; mitochondrial DNA; taxonomy",,,,,,"Thomas, C.D., Extinction risk from climate change (2004) Nature, 427, pp. 145-148; Hill, J.K., Griffiths, H.M., Thomas, C.D., Climate change and evolutionary adaptations at species' range margins (2011) Annu. Rev. Entomol., 56, pp. 143-159; Sala, O.E., Biodiversity-Global biodiversity scenarios for the year 2100 (2000) Science, 287, pp. 1770-1774; Habel, J.C., Rodder, D., Schmitt, T., Neve, G., Global warming will affect the genetic diversity and uniqueness of Lycaena helle populations (2011) Glob. Change Biol., 17, pp. 194-205; Bickford, D., Ryptic species as a window on diversity and conservation (2007) Trends Ecol. Evol., 22, pp. 148-155; Fraser, D.J., Bernatchez, L., Adaptive evolutionary conservation: Towards a unified concept for defining conservation units (2001) Mol. Ecol., 10, pp. 2741-2752; Schmidt-Kloiber, A., Hering, D., (2011) Taxa and Autecology Database for Freshwater Organisms Version 4.0, , http://www.freshwaterecology.info, available at; (2001) Climate Change 2001: The Scientific Basis, , IPCC eds Houghton, J. T. et al.) (Cambridge Univ. Press; Pauls, S.U., Lumbsch, H.T., Haase, P., Phylogeography of the montane caddisfly Drusus discolor: Evidence for multiple refugia and periglacial survival (2006) Mol. Ecol., 15, pp. 2153-2169; Schmitt, T., Molecular biogeography of Europe: Pleistocene cycles and postglacial trends (2007) Front. Zool., 4, pp. e11; Engelhardt, C.H.M., Haase, P., Pauls, S.U., From the Western Alps across Central Europe: Postglacial recolonisation of the tufa stream specialist Rhyacophila pubescens (Insecta, Trichoptera (2011) Front. Zool., 8, pp. e10; Taubmann, J., Modelling range shif